Supervisor Inend deals with the mess hall in Outpost Hope. Aside from regulation rations that are served, she is also authorized to sell general goods and treats delivered from the Veles Colony. A popular but no-nonsense lady, she is armed with a blaster rifle and once stunned a soldier in the thighs for harassing her. Said soldier was discharged shortly after and nobody has yet dared to tempt the wrath of Supervisor Inend again. Those who came close tend to find their food particularly bland and stale, and ostracized by the auxiliary staff of Outpost Hope, which for at least one soldier had quickly led to a very public display of begging for forgiveness.

Lieutenant Marbury Grant is the newly promoted commanding officer of Cresh Company, a holding company for all new enlistees under the Special Forces Scheme. He oversees them, their conduct, takes reports from them, and eventually recommends them for transfer to a new or existing special forces squad. Dealing with usually incredibly individualistic and sometimes overly arrogant individuals, he can come off stern and no-nonsense, and would not hesitate to recommend a discharge for those who fail to comport themselves with the rules and dignity as befitting a soldier of the Republic.

These small droids are widespread.  The term "utility droid" is used for many different models that vary widely in form and function. Some of them, particularly the Duwani Mechanicals models, were at times referred as "astromech droids." 

Some models are used for advanced applied physics functions such as starship repair, astrogation, and even computer slicing and programming. Others perform more menial tasks such as janitorial duties and waste disposal.

Almost all are under one meter tall. They arre equipped either with wheeled legs or small repulsorlift generators for movement.

A dramatic, stunning display of Viscara is presented here, one that spins lazily upon an axis to showcase beautiful landscapes that ranged from towering mountain ranges to vast forests and swamps. Veles Colony is plainly marked out alongside Outpost Hope, but the display otherwise holds very little strategic value.
A plaque here indicates that this door leads to the Combat Deck.
A cabinet that displays the various campaign medals, commendations, and plaques, that have been won by the brave soldiers of Outpost Hope.

Corellia, one of the first of the Core Worlds to sign the Galactic Constitution and establish the Galactic Republic. A terrestrial world of rolling hills, dense forests, lush felds and vast seas, Corellia has served as one of the beating hearts and stubborn pillar of the Republic since its first dawn. Its importance cannot be overstated, and the Republic had fought desperately and valiantly to liberate it from the occupation of the Sith Empire since its fall. With the launch of the Corellian campaign, that liberation finally seemed possible.

The Corellian Campaign began with a spearheading operation led by Admiral Forn Dodonna. It had three stages, each referred to as a partition; in the first, multiple docks and port towns were captured in a series of strategic strikes across Corellia; in the second, a rotating chain of Republic Naval cruisers landed in the docks to disembark the planetary strike force; and the third involved a general assault by Republic forces while backed by sabotage operations from the local Corellian Resistance. While casualties were high, a beachhead was eventually established on Corellia, and the Sith's occupation of the crucial Republic world contested. 

The Corellian Campaign Medal is a military campaign medal awarded by the Galactic Republic for valor, courage and service in the liberation of Corellia. It is a seven-pointed star, representing the Five Brothers of Corellia, the star of Corell and the Galactic Republic. It is bound to a ribbon with equal width bands of blue, red and white, to represent the Republic Navy, the Republic Forces, and the untarnished purity of Corellia's ideals.
A framed copy of the Galactic Constitution, abridged to reflect the most important ideals of the Galactic Republic, has been placed here above the display cabinets.

This is a shelf containing datacards, datachits, holo-films, and even books, with literature that could be helpful to understanding the Republic and what it means to serve as a soldier of the Republic.

Discharges and Transfers, the Short Version 

- Master Chief Dace Rendall, Havoc Squad

Okay, you screwed up bad enough to want to read this volume. Or you've decided you want to give someone else the opportunity to experience the thrills and paycheck of SpecOps.

First of all, if you're being offered a censure and rank reduction, take it. Most every half-decent NCO got a pip stripped at some point. Builds character.

TRANSFERS

Republic service is volunteer only. But once you're in, you're in. However, SpecOps is volunteers amongst volunteers. We don't want anyone who isn't completely sure they want to be here.

As such you can request a transfer. Sometimes for reasons. Sometimes because a job looks promising. I won't judge. Too much.

Havoc Squad. Cresh Company. Hells, even the Mon Cala Defence Force Sanitation Division (think permanent latrine duty). This Navy offers a range of exciting ways to earn your paycheck.

DISCHARGES

If you're out, you're out. But the exact wording on your record affects some things. Things like re-enlistment prospects, certain veteran benefits and of course your fellow veterans at reunions. Here they are, in decreasing order of Master Chief approval.

1. Retirement. This is the elite few. 20 years of service. The option of Retired Reserve status. Pensions, top table and bragging rights at parades and reunions. They might even get half-decent cyberware from Approved medical clinics.

2. Honorable Discharge. Typically you've finished at least one tour, which means three years in service for most branches. You've been rated between good and excellent. Sometimes discharges might, emphasis might, be upgraded to honorable retrospectfully for particularly good post-discharge behaviour.

3. Medical Discharge. You haven't finished your tours, but Command judges that you're been rendered physically or psychologically unfit to get the job done. This sucks, and usually isn't your fault. You want to pick your destination carefully as veteran care can vary between sectors and individual worlds. Talk to one of the Veterans' Associations or a decent NCO for advice.

4. General Discharge. Unsatisfactory performance, typically involving some sort of nonjudicial punishment from your CO. If anyone tells you it's just as good as a honorable discharge they're wrong. But you do keep the medical and most other benefits.

5. Dishonorable Discharge. Means what it says. Serious offences, usually involving court-martial unless you've really screwed up. It's a big red flag on your record and closes a lot of doors.

Welcome to the Republic - Welcome, to Outpost Hope

- By Captain Tyche Vanicus

To those newly enlisted to the Armed Forces of the Republic - welcome. Rarely before has our Republic been under as great and cruel a threat as the Sith Empire that wages war against us even now, and each passing day, thousands of brave soldiers such as yourself take up arms to stand as bulwark against those who would extinguish the flames of our ideals. Every member in service of the Republic is expected to measure up to the standards of those ideals: you serve to guard the Republic, and to defend the Senate and its people. 

You have a duty at all times and under all circumstances to oppose the enemies of the Republic and to support its interests. Your words and actions will reflect upon the banner under which you fight, and be it in times of rest or in times of combat, you will remain responsible for your personal actions. You have a continuing obligation to oppose unjust and unlawful commands, and you will be expected to serve with unyielding dedication the principles of the Republic. 

Just as you have a responsibility to the Republic, the Republic has a responsibility to you; your heroisms and gallantry recognised, and your deeds and service rewarded with good faith and compensation; that you be given the tools you need to defend our Republic. Remember always that while great shall be the trials and tribulations that we will face in these interesting times, greater yet is the cause that we fight and lay our lives down for. We are soldiers in defence of a people that would be subjected to tyranny, to massacre, to brutality, should we fail. We are soldiers in defence of ideals that monsters throughout time have sought to suffocate, but it is these ideals that make life yet worth living for the countless free men and women who reside in this galaxy.

Fidelity and service, my brothers and sisters in arms. 

For the Republic and its people.

Top 10 Tips to Survive the War
- By Corporal Docker A. Barns

1. Listen to orders! Kark about it after the operation! Shove your brain aside to a dark place until the operation is over and you can give your AAR.

2. Run, don't walk! When you are under enemy fire, the best way to survive it is to KEEP MOVING!

3. Watch your buddy's back! Those Sith-spit soldiers of Mally's love to shoot your back, so watch your buddy's back and let him watch yours!

4. Clean your energy cells! Lost more than a few brothers and sisters who think that those Corellian scrap-heap blaster rifles can't go wrong. They are wrong! They can! Clean the energy cells between operations and keep them pristine!

5. DON'T. LOSE. YOUR. RIFLE! Your blaster rifle is your life! It is your new spouse! Don't lose it, or you are just a liability.

6. All the staff in the mess hall are sirs and ma'ams. Trust me, don't piss them off.

7. Keep an extra pair of socks with you at all time. This goes without saying. Don't be a sockless dimwit.

8. Don't grab a tailhead by the lekku. That's just asking to be smacked in the face. Those lekkus are sensitive!

9. Don't dig too deeply. I don't know about this one, but the locals here at Viscara keep telling me about it. They keep saying not to dig too deeply, and I am going to believe them.

10. Watch the skies! Buddy of mine lived so long because he has a sixth-sense as to artillery strikes and bombing runs. Hone your instincts for those, too, and you'll live to the end of your service.

Stay strong, brother and sister. For the Republic!

Abridged Guide to the Code and Regulations
- By Lieutenant Marbury Grant

Welcome to the Republic. Chances are, you haven't read or can't understand the library of code and regulations that govern the armed forces of the Galactic Republic. If you are part of the Special Forces, you may be of the view that you have better things to do than spend four years at the University of Coruscant learning the laws of our grand Republic. So, here's the important ones. Read them and remember them.

ONE. Follow orders. You are a soldier, not a militiaman, not a mercenary, not a bounty hunter. The Republic shelters you, feeds you, gives you protection, and arms you. You listen to orders and follow them. Don't like the orders? Voice your misgivings before the operation or after the operation.

TWO. Don't shame us. You are a soldier of the Republic, and you'll be seen as such. If you do embarrassing things, we'll all be embarrassed. Don't do embarrassing things. Don't try to snog a Jedi, or dance with a Revanite next to the pyre, or harm a civilian "by accident". The reputation of your squad, of Outpost Hope, of your commanders and the Republic, rests on you.

THREE. Don't break the law. This really falls flatly under two, but it ought go without speaking that the Republic will not tolerate the commissioning of war crimes or unlawful actions by its uniformed men and women. If you break the law, you will be tried at a military tribunal and you will face the appropriate sanctions and punishments. Don't break the law.

You are a soldier of the Republic. We will hold you to standards befitting one. Keep to those standards, and you will rise high in the ranks. Fail them, and you will either find yourself swiftly summarily discharged, or worse.

You are a soldier of the Republic. Uphold the ideals of the Republic.
